      {
        "title": "Key Points",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "header",
            "text": "Key Points",
            "level": 2
          },
          {
            "type": "list",
            "items": [
              { "text": "This is a MEDICAL EMERGENCY. Immediate steps: Resuscitation and Cross-matching." },
              { "text": "Differentiate vomiting blood (Haematemesis) from coughing blood (Haemoptysis)." },
              { "text": "Haematemesis features: Food mixed with blood, Acidic pH." },
              { "text": "Beware of 'swallowed blood' from nasopharyngeal bleeding mimicking haematemesis." },
              { "text": "Following a single GI bleed, stools may remain tarry for up to 3 days and occult blood positive for 1 month." },
              { "text": "Signs of blood loss (tachycardia, hypotension) may precede the visible manifestations of bleeding." },
              { "text": "Fresh blood in rectum usually suggests large bowel pathology, but massive upper GI bleeds can also present with fresh PR bleeding." },
              { "text": "Patients with oesophageal varices can bleed from other co-existing pathologies (e.g., Peptic Ulcer)." },
              { "text": "Microcytic hypochromic anaemia suggests previous/chronic bleeding." }
            ]
          }
        ]
